I think I wrote this up in another message in this group. You should be
able to adapt the solution to your situation.

The message subject was &quot;Dynamically generating test methods?&quot;. There
may be more than one.

Take care.

So said  Mark Derricutt  on  2/14/2003 --------------------

&gt;Hiya, having just started a new job, as way of getting my head around
&gt;some 
&gt;of the code, I was asked to write some unit tests, and after writing a
&gt;heap 
&gt;of them, I noticed that the test itself was always the same, which
just 
&gt;different settings.
&gt;
&gt;I was also told that they&#39;d like our testing guy to be able to make up
new 
&gt;tests on the fly, so I wrote a new test which loaded an XML file,
which 
&gt;took care of defining what I wanted to test for, and get back.  The
test 
&gt;code looks like this:
&gt;
&gt;   public void testUnmarshelledMessage()  {
&gt;
&gt;        try {
&gt;            File path = new File(&quot;/home/mark/testmessages&quot;);
&gt;            File[] files = path.listFiles();
&gt;
&gt;            for (int i = 0; i &lt; files.length; i++) {
&gt;                File file = files[i];
&gt;                if ( file.getName().startsWith(&quot;test&quot;) && 
&gt;file.getName().endsWith(&quot;xml&quot;)) {
&gt;                    Reader reader = new FileReader(
file.getAbsoluteFile() 
&gt;);
&gt;                    TestMessage testMessage = (TestMessage)
readObject( 
&gt;reader );
&gt;                    MessageStatus result = sender.send( 
&gt;testMessage.getMessage() );
&gt;                    assertEquals( file.getName() + &quot;(&quot; + 
&gt;testMessage.getName() + &quot;)&quot;,
&gt;                        testMessage.getResult(),
result.getStatusCode() );
&gt;                }
&gt;            }
&gt;        } catch ( Exception e ) {
&gt;            fail( e.getMessage() );
&gt;        }
&gt;
&gt;    }
&gt;
&gt;So the test finds all files starting with test and ending with xml in
the 
&gt;specified directory, calls readObject() to unmarshall the XML file
into my 
&gt;TestMessage object, and does the test, and checks the result.  This is
all 
&gt;working nicely, untill I wrote a test that failed.
&gt;
&gt;Because this test is just that, one test, once it failed, none of the
&gt;other 
&gt;XML files got processed.  So I&#39;ve been trying to think of a way around
it, 
&gt;a way to run my test method against each XML file as its own test.
&gt;
&gt;I had thought of writing a custom TestSuite which took the path, found
the 
&gt;files, and added a custom TestCase with the filename ( instead of
method 
&gt;name ), and moving the actual test code above into the custom
TestCase, 
&gt;however I&#39;m not quite sure the best way to implement this.
&gt;
&gt;Any ideas?
&gt;
&gt;Mark
